<h1>World Sim Game Universal Documentation</h1>
<p>Version covered: Ver0.2.6.b</p>
<p>Status: official documentation generated from settled code. This document records</p>
<p>implemented behavior only unless a section explicitly says &quot;To confirm&quot; or</p>
<p>&quot;Known issue&quot;.</p>
<p>Patch note: Ver0.2.6.b is a code-and-metadata patch over Ver0.2.6.</p><p>The visible version marker is <code>0.2.6.b</code>; gameplay rules are unchanged.</p>
<p>Primary source anchors:</p>
<ul>
<li>Entry/game loop: <code>src/main.c</code>, <code>src/game/game.c</code>, <code>src/game/game_loop.c</code></li>
<li>Shared state/types: <code>src/core/constants.h</code>, <code>src/core/world_types.h</code>,</li>
</ul>
<p>  <code>src/core/sim_types.h</code>, <code>src/core/game_types.h</code></p>
<ul>
<li>World generation: <code>src/world/*</code></li>
<li>World generation orchestration/progress: <code>src/game/game_worldgen.c</code>,</li>
</ul>
<p>  <code>src/core/worldgen_progress.c</code>, <code>src/render/worldgen_progress_overlay.c</code></p>
<ul>
<li>Simulation: <code>src/sim/*</code></li>
<li>Rendering: <code>src/render/*</code></li>
<li>UI/input: <code>src/ui/*</code></li>
<li>Static tables: <code>src/data/game_tables.c</code>, <code>src/data/game_tables.h</code></li>
<li>Province names: <code>src/data/province_names.c</code>,</li>
</ul>
<p>  <code>data/province_names_1000_bilingual_v2.tsv</code></p>
<ul>
<li>Save/load: <code>src/io/*</code></li>
</ul>
<h2>Previous Ver0.2.5 Freeze Delta Index</h2>
<p>Preserved from the previous official baseline. Ver0.2.5 updated the Ver0.2.4.a</p>
<p>documentation baseline. The main implemented</p>
<p>changes are:</p>
<ul>
<li>Map/UI layout: default map size is now 720x500, large map is 864x600, frame</li>
</ul>
<p>  timer target is 16 ms, and the side panel can collapse into a handle.</p>
<ul>
<li>Map display modes now include <code>DISPLAY_ROUTE_POTENTIAL</code> / Routes / 航道潜力网.</li>
<li>Water is split through a reusable shallow/deep water-depth query cache instead</li>
</ul>
<p>  of only local ad hoc coast checks.</p>
<ul>
<li>Island ports are actively backfilled after region/civilization setup so viable</li>
</ul>
<p>  coastal islands can receive region and city ports.</p>
<ul>
<li>Sea lanes now derive from <code>route_potential</code>: shallow network edges and deep</li>
</ul>
<p>  long-range edges are built before active lane selection.</p>
<ul>
<li>Overseas expansion diagnostics now distinguish own port count, shallow path</li>
</ul>
<p>  blockage, deep-sea locks, and route-potential reachability.</p>
<ul>
<li>Diplomacy relation changes can create map-line animations for peace, tension,</li>
</ul>
<p>  war, truce, and vassal/release events.</p>
<ul>
<li>Country overview adds vassal action buttons for releasing a direct vassal or</li>
</ul>
<p>  requesting independence-style release from vassal state.</p>
<ul>
<li>Technology pacing is much faster and now uses <code>technology_required_months_for_civ()</code></li>
</ul>
<p>  consistently in simulation and tech UI arrival estimates.</p>
<ul>
<li>Plague fog rendering now throttles fog-cache rebuilds and exposes rebuild stats</li>
</ul>
<p>  in the debug/performance panel.</p>
<p>New or heavily changed source anchors:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>src/sim/route_potential.c</code>, <code>src/sim/route_potential.h</code></li>
<li><code>src/render/diplomacy_map_anim.c</code>, <code>src/render/diplomacy_map_anim.h</code></li>
<li><code>src/render/panel_country_actions.c</code>, <code>src/render/panel_country_actions.h</code></li>
<li><code>src/world/terrain_query.c</code>, <code>src/world/terrain_query.h</code></li>
<li><code>src/sim/ports.c</code>, <code>src/sim/sea_lanes.c</code>, <code>src/sim/maritime.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/ui/ui_layout.c</code>, <code>src/ui/ui_forms.c</code>, <code>src/render/panel_map.c</code></li>
</ul>
<h2>Ver0.2.6.b Freeze Delta Index</h2>
<p>This version updates the Ver0.2.5 official documentation baseline. The main</p>
<p>implemented changes are:</p>
<ul>
<li>Source version metadata is now <code>WORLD_SIM_VERSION "0.2.6.b"</code>, matching the user-declared Ver0.2.6.b freeze.</li>
<li>
<li>World generation flow was moved out of <code>game.c</code> into</li>
</ul>
<p>  <code>src/game/game_worldgen.c</code> and now runs through progress stages, repaint</p>
<p>  callbacks, route statistics capture, and a modal map overlay.</p>
<ul>
<li>Worldgen progress state lives in <code>src/core/worldgen_progress.c</code> and is drawn by</li>
</ul>
<p>  both the World tab status card and <code>src/render/worldgen_progress_overlay.c</code>.</p>
<ul>
<li>Build wiring added <code>game_worldgen.c</code>, <code>worldgen_progress.c</code>,</li>
</ul>
<p>  <code>province_names.c</code>, <code>diplomacy_contact.c</code>, <code>panel_country_events.c</code>,</p>
<p>  <code>panel_debug_worldgen.c</code>, and <code>worldgen_progress_overlay.c</code>.</p>
<ul>
<li>Map display buttons now expose five modes: Political, Geography, Climate,</li>
</ul>
<p>  Regions, and Routes. <code>DISPLAY_ALL</code> still exists in the enum as legacy/internal</p>
<p>  behavior, but it is no longer part of the normal button list.</p>
<ul>
<li>Province/natural-region naming was added through</li>
</ul>
<p>  <code>data/province_names_1000_bilingual_v2.tsv</code> and</p>
<p>  <code>src/data/province_names.c</code>. Regions now have <code>name_id</code>, snapshots copy</p>
<p>  localized region names, resources/details use province names, and map labels</p>
<p>  can draw province labels.</p>
<ul>
<li>Save format advanced to <code>MAP_SAVE_VERSION 7</code> so region <code>name_id</code> is saved;</li>
</ul>
<p>  older region saves are loaded through legacy structs and then assigned missing</p>
<p>  names.</p>
<ul>
<li>Country overview recent events are now rendered by</li>
</ul>
<p>  <code>src/render/panel_country_events.c</code>, with per-country filtering, scroll state,</p>
<p>  clickable country chips, and UID validation.</p>
<ul>
<li>Diplomacy contact logic moved into <code>src/sim/diplomacy_contact.c</code> with contact</li>
</ul>
<p>  kinds for land, shallow sea, deep sea, and vassal proxy contact. Relations can</p>
<p>  decay to none after 10 distant-known years with no current contact.</p>
<ul>
<li>War-front detection now uses diplomacy direct-contact kinds instead of scanning</li>
</ul>
<p>  cities/sea lanes directly in <code>war_front.c</code>.</p>
<ul>
<li>Route-potential limits expanded: potential edges are capped at 4096, path points</li>
</ul>
<p>  at 192, sea lanes at 1024, and shallow network max ports at 7. Deep backbone</p>
<p>  construction now tries to connect remaining shallow components and reports</p>
<p>  connected/disconnected network stats.</p>
<ul>
<li>Diplomacy map animations for peace/tense/war-start events now require current</li>
</ul>
<p>  diplomacy contact, preventing distant stale relations from animating.</p>
<ul>
<li>War diplomacy cards now show a battle countdown, mirrored peace-pressure bars,</li>
</ul>
<p>  and use <code>war_peace_pressure_between()</code> from simulation instead of a panel-local</p>
<p>  estimate.</p>
<p>New or heavily changed source anchors:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>src/game/game_worldgen.c</code>, <code>src/game/game_worldgen.h</code></li>
<li><code>src/core/worldgen_progress.c</code>, <code>src/core/worldgen_progress.h</code></li>
<li><code>src/render/worldgen_progress_overlay.c</code>, <code>src/render/worldgen_progress_overlay.h</code></li>
<li><code>src/render/panel_debug_worldgen.c</code>, <code>src/render/panel_debug_worldgen.h</code></li>
<li><code>src/data/province_names.c</code>, <code>src/data/province_names.h</code></li>
<li><code>data/province_names_1000_bilingual_v2.tsv</code></li>
<li><code>src/render/panel_country_events.c</code>, <code>src/render/panel_country_events.h</code></li>
<li><code>src/sim/diplomacy_contact.c</code></li>
</ul>
<h2>1. Game Overview</h2>
<p>World Sim Game is a Windows graphical civilization sandbox prototype written in C.</p>
<p>The player generates a procedural world, creates or seeds civilizations, and lets</p>
<p>monthly simulation systems advance automatically.</p>
<p>Implemented player actions:</p>
<ul>
<li>Generate a new world from the World Generation tab or shortcut.</li>
<li>Choose map size: Small 576x400, Medium 720x500, Large 864x600.</li>
<li>Set initial civilization count.</li>
<li>Add or edit civilizations from UI form controls.</li>
<li>Change selected civilization color.</li>
<li>Select tiles/countries, locate countries, and highlight countries from panels or logs.</li>
<li>Switch map display modes and side-panel tabs/subtabs, including the route</li>
</ul>
<p>  potential display mode.</p>
<ul>
<li>Collapse/expand the side panel with the side handle.</li>
<li>Start/pause auto-run and choose one of five target month speeds: Observe</li>
</ul>
<p>  10s/mo, Slow 5s/mo, Normal 1s/mo, Fast 0.25s/mo, Max 0.1s/mo.</p>
<ul>
<li>Open the pause menu, resume, view version log, save, load, or exit.</li>
</ul>
<p>Core data relationship:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>Tile</code> stores geography, climate, ecology, resource feature, owner,</li>
</ul>
<p>  province id, natural region id, elevation, moisture, temperature, variation,</p>
<p>  and river flag.</p>
<ul>
<li><code>NaturalRegion</code> groups land tiles into geography-aware regions and tracks</li>
</ul>
<p>  ownership, city binding, port site, neighbors, dominant terrain/climate/ecology,</p>
<p>  natural defense, movement difficulty, development, and disconnection state.</p>
<ul>
<li><code>City</code> is the administrative anchor for a province. In current code, province</li>
</ul>
<p>  ids are city ids.</p>
<ul>
<li><code>Civilization</code> stores country state: identity, color, alive flag, population,</li>
</ul>
<p>  core metrics, technology, capital city, disorder buckets, plague recovery,</p>
<p>  collapse grace, and event/simulation flags.</p>
<ul>
<li><code>CountrySummary</code>, <code>RegionSummary</code>, and <code>PopulationSummary</code> are derived views</li>
</ul>
<p>  rebuilt or cached by simulation modules.</p>
<p>Important boundary:</p>
<ul>
<li>World generation builds physical map data.</li>
<li>Simulation may depend on world data.</li>
<li>Rendering should be read-only. Some render paths already use <code>RenderSnapshot</code>;</li>
</ul>
<p>  some legacy paths still read globals directly. See Performance Architecture.</p>
<h2>2. Runtime Flow</h2>
<p>Startup:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>main()</code> in <code>src/main.c</code> dispatches to <code>run_game()</code>.</li>
<li>Probe modes exist for deterministic validation, including expansion and</li>
</ul>
<p>  technology stage 10 probes.</p>
<ul>
<li><code>run_game()</code> initializes Win32/GDI+, render snapshots, UI forms, and the main</li>
</ul>
<p>  message loop.</p>
<p>New world request:</p>
<ul>
<li>Source: <code>src/game/game_worldgen.c</code>.</li>
<li><code>game_request_new_world_with_progress(HWND)</code> builds <code>WorldGenConfig</code> from</li>
</ul>
<p>  UI slider globals and drives visible generation stages.</p>
<ul>
<li>It resets diplomacy, war, plague, simulation state, dirty flags, ports, and</li>
</ul>
<p>  natural regions.</p>
<ul>
<li>It calls <code>generate_world_with_config()</code>.</li>
<li>It calls <code>regions_generate(region_size_slider)</code>.</li>
<li>It runs <code>ports_ensure_island_ports()</code>, <code>province_names_assign_all()</code>, and</li>
</ul>
<p>  region cache invalidation before civilization placement.</p>
<ul>
<li>It seeds default civilizations through <code>simulation_seed_default_civilizations()</code>.</li>
<li>Ver0.2.5 additionally ensures island ports and rebuilds route potential after</li>
</ul>
<p>  region/civilization setup via <code>ports_ensure_island_ports()</code> and</p>
<p>  <code>route_potential_rebuild()</code>.</p>
<ul>
<li>Ver0.2.6.b records route stats after route-potential rebuild, then finalizes by</li>
</ul>
<p>  rebuilding maritime routes, updating diplomacy contacts, repairing colors, and</p>
<p>  publishing a render snapshot.</p>
<ul>
<li>It publishes a render snapshot.</li>
</ul>
<p>Worldgen progress:</p>
<ul>
<li>Source: <code>src/core/worldgen_progress.c</code>, <code>src/render/worldgen_progress_overlay.c</code>,</li>
</ul>
<p>  <code>src/render/panel_worldgen.c</code>, <code>src/render/panel_debug_worldgen.c</code>.</p>
<ul>
<li>Stages are Idle, Terrain generation, Water depth calculation, Natural regions,</li>
</ul>
<p>  Port sites, Shallow sea route network, Deep sea route backbone, Civilization</p>
<p>  placement, Finalizing, and Done.</p>
<ul>
<li>Progress stores overall percent, target percent, stage index/count, stage</li>
</ul>
<p>  current/total, bilingual message buffers, stage timings, total time, and route</p>
<p>  candidate/shallow/deep stats.</p>
<ul>
<li>During active progress, <code>render_world()</code> draws a dark map viewport and the</li>
</ul>
<p>  progress overlay instead of the normal cached map.</p>
<p>Frame vs month:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>WM_TIMER</code> drives frame ticks at <code>FRAME_TIMER_MS</code>. Ver0.2.5 target is</li>
</ul>
<p>  16 ms per frame.</p>
<ul>
<li><code>game_loop_tick_frame()</code> updates render-only plague animation, records profiler</li>
</ul>
<p>  frame data, consumes completed simulation visual ticks, and requests repaint</p>
<p>  when visuals, diplomacy map animations, or dirty flags changed.</p>
<ul>
<li>Auto-run does not directly run an entire month in the paint path. It schedules</li>
</ul>
<p>  month work through <code>simulation_worker</code> and <code>simulation_scheduler</code>.</p>
<p>Monthly simulation phases:</p>
<p>Source: <code>src/sim/simulation_month.c</code></p>
<ol>
<li><code>SIM_MONTH_RESOURCES</code>: optionally scans owned tiles and computes resource scores.</li>
<li><code>SIM_MONTH_CIVS</code>: updates disorder/adaptation and technology.</li>
<li><code>SIM_MONTH_GROWTH_PORTS</code>: updates population, province cache, ports, migration.</li>
<li><code>SIM_MONTH_EXPANSION</code>: runs bounded expansion work by civilization.</li>
<li><code>SIM_MONTH_PLAGUE</code>: runs batched plague updates.</li>
<li><code>SIM_MONTH_RANDOM_EVENT</code>: attempts plague random outbreak and legacy events.</li>
<li><code>SIM_MONTH_TERRITORY</code>: repairs capital/integrity state only when territory changed.</li>
<li><code>SIM_MONTH_DIPLOMACY</code>: refreshes contact data.</li>
<li><code>SIM_MONTH_CALENDAR</code>: advances month/year; yearly systems run here.</li>
</ol>
<p>Yearly systems:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>diplomacy_update_year()</code></li>
<li><code>vassal_update_year()</code></li>
<li><code>war_update_year()</code></li>
<li><code>territory_integrity_update_year()</code></li>
<li><code>collapse_update_decade()</code> every 25 years</li>
<li><code>collapse_update_immediate()</code> after each month</li>
</ul>
<h2>3. UI / UX Map</h2>
<p>Top bar:</p>
<ul>
<li>Source: <code>src/render/panel_info.c</code></li>
<li>Shows version/year/month and high-level controls.</li>
<li>Uses <code>draw_top_bar()</code>.</li>
<li>Ver0.2.6.b map mode buttons show Political, Geography, Climate, Regions, and</li>
</ul>
<p>  Routes. The older All button is not in <code>MAP_DISPLAY_MODES</code>.</p>
<p>Bottom bar:</p>
<ul>
<li>Source: <code>src/render/panel_map.c</code></li>
<li>Shows play/pause and speed controls. Ver0.2.5 speed labels are icon-forward</li>
</ul>
<p>  controls mapped to Observe 10s/mo, Slow 5s/mo, Normal 1s/mo, Fast 0.25s/mo,</p>
<p>  and Max 0.1s/mo.</p>
<ul>
<li>Input handled by <code>src/ui/ui.c</code> and <code>src/ui/ui_actions.c</code>.</li>
</ul>
<p>Map view:</p>
<ul>
<li>Source: <code>src/ui/ui_layout.c</code>, <code>src/render/render.c</code>, <code>src/render/map_render.c</code></li>
<li>Left click selects a tile/country.</li>
<li>Right drag pans.</li>
<li>Mouse wheel zooms around cursor.</li>
<li>When the side panel is expanded, mouse wheel over the panel scrolls panel</li>
</ul>
<p>  content; when collapsed, the wheel controls map zoom.</p>
<ul>
<li><code>get_map_viewport_rect()</code>, <code>ui_map_view_clamp()</code>, and</li>
</ul>
<p>  <code>ui_side_panel_apply_state()</code> keep map layout centered/clamped against the</p>
<p>  collapsed or expanded panel width.</p>
<ul>
<li><code>ui_select_civ()</code>, <code>ui_highlight_civ()</code>, and <code>ui_locate_civ()</code> manage selection,</li>
</ul>
<p>  highlight pulses, and map offsets.</p>
<p>Panel tabs:</p>
<ul>
<li>Defined by <code>PanelTab</code> in <code>src/ui/ui_types.h</code>.</li>
<li>Current tabs: Country, Population, Plague, World, Debug.</li>
<li>Rendering dispatcher: <code>draw_side_panel()</code> in <code>src/render/panel_map.c</code>.</li>
</ul>
<p>Country tab:</p>
<ul>
<li>Source: <code>src/render/panel_country.c</code>, <code>src/render/panel_country_detail.c</code></li>
<li>Ver0.2.5 action helpers live in <code>src/render/panel_country_actions.c</code>.</li>
<li>Ver0.2.6.b recent-event cards live in <code>src/render/panel_country_events.c</code>.</li>
<li>Supports all-country list, selected-country detail, sorting, scrolling, and</li>
</ul>
<p>  back-to-list behavior.</p>
<ul>
<li>Sort columns: population, provinces, army, tech, disorder.</li>
<li>Subtabs: Overview, Technology, Decision, Population, Resources, Diplomacy,</li>
</ul>
<p>  Disorder.</p>
<p>Overview actions:</p>
<ul>
<li>Civil Unrest action remains available through the country overview action hit</li>
</ul>
<p>  path.</p>
<ul>
<li>If the selected country is a vassal, the overview can show an Independence</li>
</ul>
<p>  button. Implementation routes the click to <code>game_request_release_vassal()</code>,</p>
<p>  which calls <code>vassal_release()</code>.</p>
<ul>
<li>If the selected country has direct vassals, Release buttons are shown for those</li>
</ul>
<p>  vassals. If there are no direct vassals, a disabled No vassals row is shown.</p>
<p>Overview recent events:</p>
<ul>
<li>The overview filters recent structured event entries to the selected country.</li>
<li>Cards draw localized event text and clickable country chips from stable event</li>
</ul>
<p>  snapshots.</p>
<ul>
<li>Mouse wheel over the recent-event area scrolls that sub-list before falling back</li>
</ul>
<p>  to normal country panel scrolling.</p>
<ul>
<li>Clicking a country chip highlights the country only if the current slot uid still</li>
</ul>
<p>  matches the event snapshot uid.</p>
<p>Technology subtab:</p>
<ul>
<li>Source: <code>src/render/panel_country_tech.c</code></li>
<li>Shows stage track, current stage, progress to next, bonus grid, next stage,</li>
</ul>
<p>  progress balance, and stage detail.</p>
<p>Decision subtab:</p>
<ul>
<li>Source: <code>src/render/panel_country_decision.c</code>,</li>
</ul>
<p>  <code>src/sim/decision_snapshot.c</code></p>
<ul>
<li>Shows intent, reachability, territory integrity, decision funnel, countdowns,</li>
</ul>
<p>  and last attempt reasons.</p>
<p>Population subtab:</p>
<ul>
<li>Source: <code>src/render/panel_country_population.c</code></li>
<li>Shows country and city population summaries.</li>
</ul>
<p>Resources subtab:</p>
<ul>
<li>Source: <code>src/render/panel_country_resources.c</code></li>
<li>Shows resource output, technology/disorder modifiers, and selected tile or</li>
</ul>
<p>  province inspection.</p>
<p>Diplomacy subtab:</p>
<ul>
<li>Source: <code>src/render/panel_country_diplomacy.c</code>,</li>
</ul>
<p>  <code>src/render/panel_country_diplomacy_cards.c</code></p>
<ul>
<li>Views: peace/tense, war/truce, tribute/vassal, other.</li>
<li>Ver0.2.5 relation cards use denser templates: peace/tense focus on tension</li>
</ul>
<p>  risk and peace gap, war focuses on next battle/losses/peace pressure, and</p>
<p>  vassal cards focus on tribute, callable soldiers, and overlord burden.</p>
<p>Disorder subtab:</p>
<ul>
<li>Source: <code>src/render/panel_country_disorder.c</code></li>
<li>Shows pressure sources, recovery components, active effects, plague status,</li>
</ul>
<p>  and collapse risk.</p>
<p>World Generation tab:</p>
<ul>
<li>Source: <code>src/render/panel_worldgen.c</code>, <code>src/ui/ui_worldgen_layout.c</code>,</li>
</ul>
<p>  <code>src/ui/ui_sliders.c</code></p>
<ul>
<li>Shows map size selector, sliders, initial civilization count, color palette,</li>
</ul>
<p>  and setup stages.</p>
<ul>
<li>Ver0.2.5 adds Random buttons for Physical World, Advanced Terrain Bias, and</li>
</ul>
<p>  Civilization Setup. These randomize UI configuration/form fields, not hidden</p>
<p>  simulation state.</p>
<ul>
<li>Ver0.2.6.b adds an in-panel worldgen progress card that mirrors the global</li>
</ul>
<p>  generation progress state.</p>
<p>Population global tab:</p>
<ul>
<li>Source: <code>src/render/panel_population_page.c</code></li>
<li>Shows global age structure, loss/pressure summary, and ranking.</li>
</ul>
<p>Plague tab:</p>
<ul>
<li>Source: <code>src/render/panel_plague_page.c</code></li>
<li>Shows map overlay opacity, active infected cities, country summary, and spread</li>
</ul>
<p>  factors. The fog opacity slider is viewer-only.</p>
<p>Debug tab:</p>
<ul>
<li>Source: <code>src/render/panel_debug.c</code></li>
<li>Shows map layers, target speed, event log, expansion gate, legacy/internal</li>
</ul>
<p>  information, performance, scheduler, snapshot, and render cache details.</p>
<ul>
<li>Event log supports filters, scroll freeze, top reset, country chips, and clear</li>
</ul>
<p>  highlight.</p>
<ul>
<li>Ver0.2.5 debug output includes route-potential/sea-lane counts and plague fog</li>
</ul>
<p>  cache rebuild statistics.</p>
<ul>
<li>Ver0.2.6.b debug output adds Worldgen Timing rows for total, terrain, regions,</li>
</ul>
<p>  ports, route timing, candidates, shallow/deep edges, shallow networks, and deep</p>
<p>  backbone connectivity.</p>
<h2>4. World Generation</h2>
<p>Source files:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>src/world/world_gen.c</code>, <code>src/world/world_gen.h</code></li>
<li><code>src/world/noise.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/world/mountain_gen.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/world/rivers.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/world/world_smoothing.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/world/ports.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/world/terrain_query.c</code></li>
</ul>
<p>WorldGenConfig fields:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>ocean</code></li>
<li><code>continent</code> (UI concept: fragmentation/continent shape)</li>
<li><code>relief</code></li>
<li><code>moisture</code></li>
<li><code>drought</code></li>
<li><code>vegetation</code></li>
<li><code>bias_forest</code></li>
<li><code>bias_desert</code></li>
<li><code>bias_mountain</code></li>
<li><code>bias_wetland</code></li>
<li><code>seed</code></li>
<li><code>random_seed</code></li>
</ul>
<p>Generation order:</p>
<ol>
<li>Seed RNG.</li>
<li>Generate elevation, moisture, and temperature fields with value noise.</li>
<li>Compute target land percent from ocean slider.</li>
<li>Smooth fields based on continent/fragmentation.</li>
<li>Add relief/mountain uplift passes.</li>
<li>Compute sea level and ocean distance.</li>
<li>Classify geography and climate per tile.</li>
<li>Smooth small artifacts.</li>
<li>Classify ecology and resource feature.</li>
<li>Apply continuous mountain chains.</li>
<li>Generate rivers.</li>
</ol>
<p>Slider effects:</p>
<ul>
<li>Ocean: increases sea coverage. At 0, generation switches to land-first logic.</li>
</ul>
<p>  Ocean also affects coast band and sea-distance climate moderation.</p>
<ul>
<li>Fragment/Continent: affects noise weighting and smoothing. Higher values make</li>
</ul>
<p>  fragmented terrain and smaller features more likely.</p>
<ul>
<li>Relief: affects elevation, mountain/hill/canyon classification, uplift passes,</li>
</ul>
<p>  and mountain-chain strength.</p>
<ul>
<li>Moisture: raises moisture field and river target count; affects wet climates,</li>
</ul>
<p>  ecology, lakes, wetlands, deltas, and resources.</p>
<ul>
<li>Drought: subtracts moisture through dry shift and raises desert/semi-arid</li>
</ul>
<p>  likelihood with desert bias.</p>
<ul>
<li>Vegetation: affects forest ecology through forest bias.</li>
<li>Terrain Bias / Forest: raises chance of forest/rainforest ecology.</li>
<li>Terrain Bias / Desert: strengthens dry climate classification.</li>
<li>Terrain Bias / Mountain: increases mountain thresholds, uplift, chain count,</li>
</ul>
<p>  and chain strength.</p>
<ul>
<li>Natural Regions / Region Size: not part of <code>WorldGenConfig</code>; it is passed to</li>
</ul>
<p>  <code>regions_generate()</code> after terrain generation.</p>
<p>Geography categories:</p>
<ul>
<li>Ocean, Coast, Plain, Hill, Mountain, Plateau, Basin, Canyon, Volcano, Lake,</li>
</ul>
<p>  Bay, Delta, Wetland, Oasis, Island.</p>
<p>Climate categories:</p>
<ul>
<li>Tropical Rainforest, Tropical Monsoon, Tropical Savanna, Desert, Semi-Arid,</li>
</ul>
<p>  Mediterranean, Oceanic, Temperate Monsoon, Continental, Subarctic, Tundra,</p>
<p>  Ice Cap, Alpine, Highland Plateau.</p>
<p>Ecology categories:</p>
<ul>
<li>None, Forest, Rainforest, Grassland, Desert, Tundra, Swamp, Bamboo, Mangrove.</li>
</ul>
<p>Resource features:</p>
<ul>
<li>None, Farmland, Pasture, Forest Resource, Mine, Fishery, Salt Lake, Geothermal.</li>
</ul>
<h2>5. Terrain Resources</h2>
<p>Source:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>src/world/terrain_query.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/data/game_tables.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/data/game_tables.h</code></li>
</ul>
<p><code>tile_stats(x, y)</code> combines:</p>
<ul>
<li>Geography table stats.</li>
<li>Climate table stats.</li>
<li>Ecology table stats.</li>
<li>Resource feature table stats.</li>
<li>River bonuses.</li>
<li>Tile resource variation.</li>
<li>Moisture adjustments.</li>
</ul>
<p>TerrainStats fields:</p>
<ul>
<li>food</li>
<li>livestock</li>
<li>wood</li>
<li>stone</li>
<li>minerals</li>
<li>water</li>
<li>pop_capacity</li>
<li>money</li>
<li>habitability</li>
<li>attack</li>
<li>defense</li>
</ul>
<p>Uses:</p>
<ul>
<li>City radius and site scoring.</li>
<li>Country summary.</li>
<li>Resource pressure.</li>
<li>Technology progress requirement.</li>
<li>Expansion need.</li>
<li>Population carrying capacity.</li>
<li>UI tile/province/country resource display.</li>
</ul>
<h2>6. Map Rendering</h2>
<p>Source files:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>src/render/render.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/render/terrain_present.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/render/render_common.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/render/map_render.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/render/cartography_layers.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/render/contour_paths.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/render/vector_paths.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/render/border_paths.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/render/sea_lane_render.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/render/plague_render.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/render/plague_visual.c</code></li>
</ul>
<p>Display modes:</p>
<ul>
<li>Political</li>
<li>Geography</li>
<li>Climate</li>
<li>Regions</li>
<li>Routes / Route Potential</li>
</ul>
<p>Implementation note:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>DisplayMode</code> still defines <code>DISPLAY_OVERVIEW</code> and <code>DISPLAY_ALL</code>, and</li>
</ul>
<p>  some rendering/legend code still has cases for them. Ver0.2.6.b normal UI mode</p>
<p>  buttons use only the five <code>MAP_DISPLAY_MODES</code> listed above, with Political as</p>
<p>  the default.</p>
<p>Terrain colors:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>geography_color()</code>, <code>climate_color()</code>, and <code>overview_color()</code> live in</li>
</ul>
<p>  <code>src/render/render_common.c</code>.</p>
<ul>
<li><code>tile_display_color()</code> switches by display mode.</li>
</ul>
<p>Water depth:</p>
<ul>
<li>Source: <code>src/world/terrain_query.c</code> and <code>src/world/terrain_query.h</code>.</li>
<li><code>world_water_depth_at()</code> returns none, shallow, or deep water.</li>
<li><code>world_is_shallow_water()</code> and <code>world_is_deep_water()</code> are used by ports,</li>
</ul>
<p>  sea navigation, rendering, and maritime reachability.</p>
<ul>
<li>The visual blend uses distance-to-land: shallow water near the coast and deeper</li>
</ul>
<p>  water farther out. Logic shallow range and visual blend range are cached and</p>
<p>  invalidated through terrain stats/cache invalidation.</p>
<p>Route potential rendering:</p>
<ul>
<li>Source: <code>src/render/sea_lane_render.c</code>.</li>
<li>When <code>display_mode == DISPLAY_ROUTE_POTENTIAL</code>, the renderer draws route</li>
</ul>
<p>  potential nodes and shallow/deep potential edges before active lane overlays.</p>
<ul>
<li>Shallow potential edges are cyan-style dashed links; deep potential edges are</li>
</ul>
<p>  blue/purple dashed links. Selected-civilization nodes receive stronger focus.</p>
<p>Static map cache:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>draw_cached_static_map()</code> maintains separate layer caches:</li>
</ul>
<p>  terrain, coast, political, border/static, and UI.</p>
<ul>
<li>Dirty flags decide rebuilds.</li>
<li>During zoom/pan preview, <code>draw_map_cache_preview()</code> transforms the last cached</li>
</ul>
<p>  map before high-quality layers rebuild.</p>
<p>Terrain bitmap cache:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>terrain_present.c</code> keeps a base terrain surface and a screen-space surface.</li>
<li>Uses <code>StretchBlt</code>; stretch mode switches between <code>HALFTONE</code> and <code>COLORONCOLOR</code></li>
</ul>
<p>  depending on tile size and preview mode.</p>
<p>Borders/coasts:</p>
<ul>
<li>Cartographic path layers draw political fills, coast halo, region borders,</li>
</ul>
<p>  province borders, country borders, and coastlines.</p>
<ul>
<li><code>contour_paths.c</code> has cached contour paths keyed by dirty revisions.</li>
<li><code>border_paths.c</code> also contains older alpha-mask/blur drawing helpers.</li>
</ul>
<p>Dynamic overlays:</p>
<ul>
<li>Cities and ports.</li>
<li>Country highlight.</li>
<li>Maritime routes/sea lanes.</li>
<li>Plague region overlay and render-only plague animation.</li>
<li>Labels.</li>
</ul>
<p>Icons:</p>
<ul>
<li>Source: <code>src/render/icons.c</code>, <code>src/render/icons.h</code>, <code>assets/icons/*</code></li>
<li>City markers use outpost/village/town/city/capital icons.</li>
<li>Harbor marker uses <code>ICON_HARBOR</code>.</li>
</ul>
<p>RenderSnapshot:</p>
<ul>
<li>Source: <code>src/core/render_snapshot.c</code>, <code>src/core/render_snapshot.h</code></li>
<li>Captures tiles, civs, cities, sea lanes, plague state, and recent events for</li>
</ul>
<p>  render-side reads.</p>
<ul>
<li>Snapshot text and clickable event payload are paired through copied</li>
</ul>
<p>  <code>EventLogEntry</code> data.</p>
<p>To confirm:</p>
<ul>
<li>Some render modules still use legacy global state while snapshot migration is</li>
</ul>
<p>  in progress. This is implementation state, not intended gameplay.</p>
<h2>7. Natural Regions, Provinces, Cities, Capitals, Ports</h2>
<p>Natural regions:</p>
<ul>
<li>Source: <code>src/sim/regions.c</code>, <code>src/sim/regions_shape.c</code>,</li>
</ul>
<p>  <code>src/sim/region_boundary.c</code></p>
<ul>
<li><code>regions_generate(region_size_value)</code> creates geography-aware land regions.</li>
<li>Boundary costs are influenced by mountains, canyons, rivers, coastlines,</li>
</ul>
<p>  climate/ecology transitions, and compactness.</p>
<ul>
<li><code>NaturalRegion</code> stores neighbors, average/total stats, dominant geography,</li>
</ul>
<p>  climate, ecology, defense, difficulty, habitability, development, cradle,</p>
<p>  resource diversity, port site, and disconnection data.</p>
<ul>
<li>Ver0.2.6.b adds <code>NaturalRegion.name_id</code>. Names are assigned by</li>
</ul>
<p>  <code>province_names_assign_all()</code> during region generation and by</p>
<p>  <code>province_names_assign_missing()</code> when loading older save data.</p>
<p>Province and city:</p>
<ul>
<li>Source: <code>src/sim/province.c</code>, <code>src/sim/province_partition.c</code>,</li>
</ul>
<p>  <code>src/sim/simulation.c</code></p>
<ul>
<li><code>world_create_city()</code> creates a city and initializes population.</li>
<li><code>province_claim_city_region()</code> claims a geography-aware province around that</li>
</ul>
<p>  city.</p>
<ul>
<li>Current province id is the city id.</li>
<li>Province selection uses city radius, terrain cost, rivers, mountains, coast,</li>
</ul>
<p>  and enemy border penalties.</p>
<p>Province names:</p>
<ul>
<li>Source: <code>src/data/province_names.c</code>, <code>src/data/province_names.h</code>, and</li>
</ul>
<p>  <code>data/province_names_1000_bilingual_v2.tsv</code>.</p>
<ul>
<li>The TSV contains bilingual candidate names. Code loads up to 1100 entries and</li>
</ul>
<p>  infers tags such as coast, harbor, river, mountain, forest, wetland, desert,</p>
<p>  border, core, lake, highland, and lowland.</p>
<ul>
<li>Region context tags are inferred from port site, dominant geography/climate/</li>
</ul>
<p>  ecology, average water, development score, neighbor count, and natural defense.</p>
<ul>
<li>Selection keeps a small top-choice pool and avoids duplicate assigned names when</li>
</ul>
<p>  possible.</p>
<ul>
<li><code>province_display_name()</code> provides localized display names and falls back to</li>
</ul>
<p>  Natural Region N if no valid name exists.</p>
<p>Province labels and snapshot:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>RenderSnapshot</code> now copies <code>SnapshotRegion</code> entries with localized region</li>
</ul>
<p>  names.</p>
<ul>
<li><code>draw_province_labels()</code> draws province labels for sufficiently large visible</li>
</ul>
<p>  regions, skipping climate and route-potential modes and avoiding label overlap.</p>
<ul>
<li>Country/resources and info panels use <code>province_display_name()</code> for selected</li>
</ul>
<p>  natural region display.</p>
<p>Capital:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>Civilization.capital_city</code> stores the capital city id.</li>
<li>Initial spawn creates a capital city in a selected region.</li>
<li>Territory integrity can repair capitals after ownership changes.</li>
</ul>
<p>Ports:</p>
<ul>
<li>World-level port helpers: <code>src/world/ports.c</code></li>
<li>Simulation port updates: <code>src/sim/ports.c</code></li>
<li>A city can become a port if its province has coast and a port site is found.</li>
<li>Port fields: <code>City.port</code>, <code>port_x</code>, <code>port_y</code>, <code>port_region</code>.</li>
</ul>
<p>Ver0.2.5 port completion:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>ports_ensure_island_ports()</code> scans land components after region generation</li>
</ul>
<p>  and after territory seeding/recalculation.</p>
<ul>
<li>Components with existing region/city ports are left alone. Tiny components under</li>
</ul>
<p>  18 tiles are excluded unless a city exists.</p>
<ul>
<li>Candidate scoring uses shallow/deep water adjacency, habitability, terrain</li>
</ul>
<p>  resource value, movement/tile cost, coast, and delta bonuses.</p>
<ul>
<li>If a region port already exists, <code>ports_activate_region_port_for_city()</code> binds</li>
</ul>
<p>  it to the administrative city during region claiming; otherwise the older</p>
<p>  <code>ports_maybe_make_city_port()</code> fallback is used.</p>
<h2>8. Civilization Metrics</h2>
<p>Seven core metrics:</p>
<ul>
<li>Governance</li>
<li>Cohesion</li>
<li>Production</li>
<li>Military</li>
<li>Commerce</li>
<li>Logistics</li>
<li>Innovation</li>
</ul>
<p>Source anchors:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>CivilizationMetric</code> in <code>src/core/sim_types.h</code></li>
<li><code>Civilization</code> fields in <code>src/core/sim_types.h</code></li>
<li><code>CIVILIZATION_METRIC_RULES</code> in <code>src/data/game_tables.h</code></li>
<li>Metric editing UI: <code>src/ui/ui_forms.c</code>, <code>src/render/panel_info.c</code></li>
</ul>
<p>Displayed in UI:</p>
<ul>
<li>Country overview/details.</li>
<li>Country cards and metric chips.</li>
<li>Civilization form fields.</li>
<li>Technology and decision panels indirectly show effects.</li>
</ul>
<p>Implemented reads:</p>
<ul>
<li>Governance: disorder recovery and vassal governance pressure context.</li>
<li>Cohesion: disorder recovery during war and stability-related displays.</li>
<li>Production: resource/country display and civilization metric table.</li>
<li>Military: mobilized soldiers and war pressure.</li>
<li>Commerce: trade fit/resource economy displays and formulas.</li>
<li>Logistics: expansion, migration, remote reach, and adaptation.</li>
<li>Innovation: technology progress requirement.</li>
</ul>
<p>Dynamic non-core metric:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>adaptation</code> exists on <code>Civilization</code> but is derived monthly from environment,</li>
</ul>
<p>  resources, culture/cohesion/logistics/innovation, hardship, and instability.</p>
<p>  It is not one of the seven core metrics.</p>
<p>To confirm:</p>
<ul>
<li>Some legacy fields remain (<code>aggression</code>, <code>defense</code>, <code>culture</code>). They still</li>
</ul>
<p>  affect diplomacy/war/UI but are not part of the seven core metric list.</p>
<h2>9. Technology System</h2>
<p>Source:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>src/sim/technology.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/data/game_tables.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/render/panel_country_tech.c</code></li>
</ul>
<p>Stages:</p>
<ul>
<li>Stage 0 - Tribal Age: no technology bonus.</li>
<li>Stage 1 - Settlement Age: expansion x1.10.</li>
<li>Stage 2 - Regional Age: expansion x1.20.</li>
<li>Stage 3 - Craft Age: resource output x1.05.</li>
<li>Stage 4 - Market Age: resource output x1.10.</li>
<li>Stage 5 - Administrative Age: resource output up to x1.20.</li>
<li>Stage 6 - Ocean Age: deep sea stability 50%, deep plague spread 50%.</li>
<li>Stage 7 - Navigation Age: deep sea stability 80%, deep plague spread 35%.</li>
<li>Stage 8 - Engineering Age: deep sea stability 90%, plague 15%, tech +10%,</li>
</ul>
<p>  defense x1.20.</p>
<ul>
<li>Stage 9 - Strategic Age: deep sea stability 99%, plague 5%, battle chance +15.</li>
<li>Stage 10 - Imperial Age: deep plague spread 0%, long-held vassals can be</li>
</ul>
<p>  annexed.</p>
<p>Progress:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>technology_initialize_civ()</code> starts civs at stage 0 and progress 0.</li>
<li><code>technology_update_month()</code> updates every living civ below stage 10.</li>
<li>Ver0.2.5 required-month calculation is centralized in</li>
</ul>
<p>  <code>technology_required_months_for_civ()</code>.</p>
<ul>
<li>Base required years are <code>78 - (innovation - 5) * 4</code>, clamped to 60-96 before</li>
</ul>
<p>  resource/pressure/high-stage modifiers.</p>
<ul>
<li>Strong resources reduce requirement by 6 years; weak resources add 6 years.</li>
<li>Low population pressure reduces requirement by 3 years; high pressure adds 4</li>
</ul>
<p>  or 8 years depending on severity.</p>
<ul>
<li>Stages 8+ apply a 92% multiplier, then the final requirement is clamped to</li>
</ul>
<p>  58-96 years.</p>
<ul>
<li>Monthly progress is affected by <code>disorder_technology_percent()</code>.</li>
<li>Stage advancement resets progress and invalidates population/resource caches.</li>
</ul>
<p>Displayed UI:</p>
<ul>
<li>Current stage and name.</li>
<li>Stage track and percent progress.</li>
<li>Time to next stage.</li>
<li>Bonus grid for current and next stage.</li>
<li>Progress balance: innovation, resources, population pressure, disorder drag.</li>
</ul>
<p>Validation:</p>
<ul>
<li>Ver0.2.4 added deterministic <code>--probe-tech10</code>.</li>
<li>Side doc reports stage 10 reached naturally at year 1178 month 2 in the probe.</li>
</ul>
<h2>10. Expansion System</h2>
<p>Source:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>src/sim/expansion.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/sim/maritime.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/sim/decision_snapshot.c</code></li>
</ul>
<p>Core structures:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>ExpansionWorkState</code></li>
<li><code>ExpansionAIDiagnostics</code></li>
<li><code>MaritimeExpansionDiagnostics</code></li>
</ul>
<p>Need and threshold:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>expansion_need_for_civ()</code> uses population pressure and resource score.</li>
<li><code>expansion_threshold_for_civ()</code> is reduced by technology expansion percent.</li>
<li>Expansion desire includes land adjacent regions, nearby regions, shallow sea,</li>
</ul>
<p>  maritime/deep reachability, population pressure, resource pressure, and</p>
<p>  expansion trait.</p>
<p>Land expansion:</p>
<ul>
<li>Preferred path is neighboring unowned natural regions.</li>
<li>Nearby land can be considered through region pathing.</li>
<li>Claiming uses <code>regions_claim_for_civ()</code>.</li>
<li>Claims can create a city or attach to an existing administrative city.</li>
</ul>
<p>Sea expansion:</p>
<ul>
<li>Nearshore/shallow-sea candidates are considered after land diagnostics.</li>
<li>Deep-sea candidates require deep sea stability from technology.</li>
<li><code>maritime_try_overseas_expansion()</code> handles overseas target collection,</li>
</ul>
<p>  route/path validation, city cap fallback, and event logging.</p>
<ul>
<li>Ver0.2.5 target reachability goes through <code>route_potential_region_reachable()</code>.</li>
<li>Shallow route candidates receive a score bonus, while diagnostics separately</li>
</ul>
<p>  report own port count and <code>blocked_no_shallow_path</code>.</p>
<p>Why expansion may not happen:</p>
<ul>
<li>Cooldown not complete.</li>
<li>Desire below threshold.</li>
<li>No reachable land/sea target.</li>
<li>No port or no port site.</li>
<li>Shallow path blocked by deep water or route-potential network limits.</li>
<li>Deep sea locked.</li>
<li>No sea entry/path.</li>
<li>City cap.</li>
<li>Random chance or low score.</li>
<li>Land targets suppress overseas targets.</li>
</ul>
<p>Decision UI:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>decision_snapshot_for_civ()</code> exposes reachability, expansion weights,</li>
</ul>
<p>  countdowns, territory integrity, and last reasons.</p>
<h2>11. Sea Lanes and Ports</h2>
<p>Source:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>src/sim/maritime.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/sim/route_potential.c</code>, <code>src/sim/route_potential.h</code></li>
<li><code>src/sim/sea_lanes.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/sim/sea_nav.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/sim/ports.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/world/ports.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/render/sea_lane_render.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/render/route_render.c</code></li>
</ul>
<p>Port generation:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>ports_maybe_make_city_port()</code> can assign a port to a city with coastal</li>
</ul>
<p>  province access.</p>
<ul>
<li><code>ports_refresh_city_regions()</code> syncs port region data.</li>
<li><code>ports_ensure_island_ports()</code> can add missing region/city ports for viable</li>
</ul>
<p>  island/coastal components.</p>
<p>Route potential graph:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>route_potential_rebuild()</code> collects natural regions with port sites/sea</li>
</ul>
<p>  entries into <code>RoutePortNode</code> records and builds potential shallow/deep edges.</p>
<ul>
<li>Shallow direct limits are derived from map dimension, clamped 14-72; shallow</li>
</ul>
<p>  networks are capped by <code>SHALLOW_NETWORK_MAX_PORTS</code> and diameter limits.</p>
<ul>
<li>Ver0.2.6.b values: potential edges cap is 4096, potential points cap is 192,</li>
</ul>
<p>  sea-lane cap is 1024, and shallow network max ports is 7.</p>
<ul>
<li>Deep direct limits are based on <code>MAP_W + MAP_H</code>, clamped from 120 to the</li>
</ul>
<p>  maximum map width plus height, and require</p>
<p>  tech stage 6 for active use. Deep network degree is capped.</p>
<ul>
<li>Ver0.2.6.b deep backbone construction records deep bridge candidates, tries deep</li>
</ul>
<p>  paths that require meaningful deep-water segments, blocks failed pairs, and</p>
<p>  attempts to connect remaining shallow-network components.</p>
<ul>
<li>Route stats now include shallow network count, small shallow networks, average</li>
</ul>
<p>  shallow size, deep bridge count/candidates, connected networks, disconnected</p>
<p>  networks, and rejection reasons such as no deep water, near shore, endpoint,</p>
<p>  diameter, and truncation.</p>
<ul>
<li><code>route_potential_region_reachable()</code> is the main query used by maritime</li>
</ul>
<p>  expansion diagnostics and target collection.</p>
<p>Route layers:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>MaritimeRoute</code> is the older route structure in <code>src/core/sim_types.h</code>.</li>
<li><code>SeaLane</code> is the active visual/logical lane structure in</li>
</ul>
<p>  <code>src/sim/sea_lanes.h</code>; Ver0.2.5 lanes are selected from route-potential edges.</p>
<ul>
<li><code>RenderSnapshot</code> copies sea lanes for rendering.</li>
</ul>
<p>Lane types:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>SEA_LANE_SHALLOW</code></li>
<li><code>SEA_LANE_DEEP</code></li>
</ul>
<p>Port statuses:</p>
<ul>
<li>isolated</li>
<li>shallow</li>
<li>deep gateway</li>
</ul>
<p>Active lane selection:</p>
<ul>
<li>Shallow lanes are sorted by distance and accepted while respecting shallow</li>
</ul>
<p>  network size and diameter limits.</p>
<ul>
<li>Deep lanes are selected from potential deep edges, require qualifying owner</li>
</ul>
<p>  technology, and use a lower degree cap.</p>
<ul>
<li>Sea-lane contact can return shallow-network contact or deep-connected contact;</li>
</ul>
<p>  trade bonus is 5 for shallow and 8 for deep-connected contact.</p>
<p>Used by:</p>
<ul>
<li>Overseas expansion.</li>
<li>Trade bonus.</li>
<li>Diplomacy contact.</li>
<li>Plague spread.</li>
<li>War front reachability through sea lanes.</li>
<li>Rendering dashed routes and infected route intensity.</li>
</ul>
<p>Technology effects:</p>
<ul>
<li>Stage 6 unlocks deep-sea capability.</li>
<li>Stages 6-10 reduce deep-sea death/plague risk through deep sea stability and</li>
</ul>
<p>  deep plague percent.</p>
<p>Known issue / migration note:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>src/render/maritime_render.c</code> notes that active build uses</li>
</ul>
<p>  <code>src/render/route_render.c</code> for <code>draw_maritime_routes()</code>. Treat</p>
<p>  <code>maritime_render.c</code> as legacy/inactive unless build wiring changes.</p>
<h2>12. Diplomacy</h2>
<p>Source:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>src/sim/diplomacy.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/sim/diplomacy.h</code></li>
<li><code>src/sim/diplomacy_contact.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/sim/war_front.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/render/panel_country_diplomacy.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/render/panel_country_diplomacy_cards.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/render/diplomacy_map_anim.c</code></li>
</ul>
<p>Diplomacy states:</p>
<ul>
<li>None</li>
<li>Peace</li>
<li>Alliance</li>
<li>Tense</li>
<li>Truce</li>
<li>War</li>
<li>Vassal</li>
</ul>
<p>Relation fields:</p>
<ul>
<li>state</li>
<li>relation_score</li>
<li>border_tension</li>
<li>trade_fit</li>
<li>resource_conflict</li>
<li>truce_years_left</li>
<li>border_length</li>
<li>natural_barrier</li>
<li>years_known</li>
<li>vassal_years</li>
<li>contact_kind</li>
<li>years_distant_known</li>
<li>overlord</li>
<li>vassal</li>
</ul>
<p>Contact:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>diplomacy_update_contacts()</code> scans/caches border contacts when dirty.</li>
<li>Sea lane contact contributes through maritime/sea-lane systems.</li>
<li>Ver0.2.6.b contact kind is represented by <code>DiplomacyContactKind</code>: none, land</li>
</ul>
<p>  border, shallow sea network, deep sea network, and vassal proxy.</p>
<ul>
<li><code>diplomacy_direct_contact_kind()</code> checks direct land or sea-network contact.</li>
<li><code>diplomacy_current_contact_kind()</code> also considers overlord/direct-vassal</li>
</ul>
<p>  control groups and can return vassal proxy contact.</p>
<p>Tension and peace:</p>
<ul>
<li>Border tension is computed from border pressure, militarism, blocked pressure,</li>
</ul>
<p>  trade fit, resources, and natural barriers.</p>
<ul>
<li>Peace can become tense when border tension is at least 55 or relation score is</li>
</ul>
<p>  below 35.</p>
<ul>
<li>Tense can return to peace when border tension drops below 35 and relation</li>
</ul>
<p>  score is above 45.</p>
<ul>
<li>Truce counts down yearly; when it reaches zero, relation returns to tense if</li>
</ul>
<p>  border tension is at least 55, otherwise peace.</p>
<ul>
<li>Ver0.2.5 logs structured peace/tense transitions and initial peace contact</li>
</ul>
<p>  events. It also reduces border-tension contribution when there is no border</p>
<p>  length.</p>
<ul>
<li>Ver0.2.6.b relations with no current contact, outside war/truce/vassal states,</li>
</ul>
<p>  decay border tension and resource conflict, zero trade fit, ease relation score</p>
<p>  toward 50, and revert to <code>DIPLOMACY_NONE</code> after 10 distant-known years.</p>
<ul>
<li>When a truce expires with no current contact, the relation returns to none</li>
</ul>
<p>  instead of peace/tense.</p>
<p>Diplomacy map animation:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>diplomacy_map_anim_consume_events()</code> reads recent structured events and</li>
</ul>
<p>  creates render-only relation-line animations.</p>
<ul>
<li>Animated event types include peace, tense, war started, truce signed, war front</li>
</ul>
<p>  severed, vassal created, vassal released, vassal transferred, and vassal</p>
<p>  peaceful independence.</p>
<ul>
<li><code>draw_diplomacy_map_animations()</code> draws curved relation arrows/markers.</li>
<li><code>diplomacy_map_anim_active()</code> keeps the frame loop repainting while animation</li>
</ul>
<p>  is active.</p>
<ul>
<li>Ver0.2.6.b requires current diplomacy contact for peace, tense, and war-start</li>
</ul>
<p>  animations so stale distant relations do not create map lines.</p>
<p>War:</p>
<ul>
<li>Tense relations compute war desire for both sides.</li>
<li>If either desire reaches 70, war may start.</li>
<li>War start still requires an active land/sea/vassal front.</li>
</ul>
<p>Alliance:</p>
<ul>
<li>Peace can become alliance when relation score is at least 78, trade fit at</li>
</ul>
<p>  least 60, and border tension at most 25.</p>
<ul>
<li>Alliance can fall back to peace if tension or resource conflict rises.</li>
</ul>
<p>Vassal:</p>
<ul>
<li>Vassal relation stores overlord/vassal ids.</li>
<li>Stage 10 overlords can annex long-held vassals after 100 vassal years.</li>
</ul>
<h2>13. Vassal System</h2>
<p>Source:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>src/sim/vassal.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/sim/vassal.h</code></li>
<li><code>src/sim/diplomacy.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/sim/simulation.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/sim/war.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/game/game.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/render/panel_country_actions.c</code></li>
</ul>
<p>Core functions:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>vassal_make()</code></li>
<li><code>vassal_release()</code></li>
<li><code>vassal_release_all()</code></li>
<li><code>vassal_normalize_all()</code></li>
<li><code>vassal_update_year()</code></li>
<li><code>vassal_resource_tribute_breakdown_from()</code></li>
<li><code>vassal_callable_soldiers()</code></li>
</ul>
<p>Implemented behavior:</p>
<ul>
<li>Vassal state is represented by <code>DIPLOMACY_VASSAL</code>.</li>
<li>A direct vassal has one direct overlord.</li>
<li>Nested vassals are normalized/transferred to root overlord.</li>
<li>Vassals do not start ordinary wars as independent actors.</li>
<li>Attacks on vassals route to overlord.</li>
<li>Direct vassals are released when overlord collapses.</li>
<li>Successors after vassal collapse remain independent.</li>
</ul>
<p>Tribute:</p>
<ul>
<li>40% of food, livestock, wood, stone, minerals, and water transfers from vassal</li>
</ul>
<p>  summary to overlord summary.</p>
<ul>
<li>Money, population, population capacity, and habitability are not tribute.</li>
<li>Ver0.2.4 UI displays only the six actually transferred resource fields.</li>
</ul>
<p>Army:</p>
<ul>
<li>Callable army is 70% of vassal current soldiers.</li>
<li>Home guard is total minus callable.</li>
<li>War support tracks current support use and support casualties.</li>
</ul>
<p>Independence:</p>
<ul>
<li>Yearly update compares vassal army to overlord army.</li>
<li>Very strong vassals may be released peacefully or start independence war.</li>
</ul>
<p>Manual release UI:</p>
<ul>
<li>Country overview vassal buttons call <code>game_request_release_vassal(vassal_id)</code>.</li>
<li>The game request validates the selected vassal and overlord, calls</li>
</ul>
<p>  <code>vassal_release()</code>, logs <code>EVENT_TYPE_VASSAL_RELEASED</code>, invalidates derived</p>
<p>  summaries/diplomacy/maritime/territory/labels, and republishes a snapshot.</p>
<ul>
<li>If a release request has no valid overlord, current code logs a debug/raw</li>
</ul>
<p>  fallback reason <code>VASSAL_RELEASE_FAILED_NO_OVERLORD</code>.</p>
<p>Governance burden:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>vassal_governance_disorder()</code> contributes a minimum disorder floor from</li>
</ul>
<p>  direct vassal count.</p>
<ul>
<li>Current documentation should be checked against code when changing this</li>
</ul>
<p>  formula because older version notes used a different expression.</p>
<h2>14. War System</h2>
<p>Source:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>src/sim/war.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/sim/war_front.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/sim/war_resolution.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/sim/diplomacy.c</code></li>
</ul>
<p>Core structure:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>ActiveWar</code></li>
</ul>
<p>Start conditions:</p>
<ul>
<li>Attacker and defender must be valid living civs.</li>
<li>Vassal attackers cannot start ordinary war.</li>
<li>If defender is a vassal, target routes to overlord.</li>
<li>An active front must exist.</li>
<li>Duplicate active war pair is rejected.</li>
</ul>
<p>Fronts:</p>
<ul>
<li>Land border.</li>
<li>Vassal land.</li>
<li>Sea lane.</li>
<li>Vassal sea.</li>
</ul>
<p>Ver0.2.6.b front detection:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>war_front_flags()</code> builds attacker/defender control groups from direct</li>
</ul>
<p>  vassals or overlord context.</p>
<ul>
<li>It now queries <code>diplomacy_direct_contact_kind()</code> for each group pair. Land</li>
</ul>
<p>  contact yields land/vassal-land fronts; shallow or deep sea-network contact</p>
<p>  yields sea/vassal-sea fronts.</p>
<ul>
<li>The older direct city/sea-lane scan was removed from <code>war_front.c</code>.</li>
</ul>
<p>Soldiers:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>mobilized_soldiers()</code> derives military strength from population and civ</li>
</ul>
<p>  military/defense/logistics context.</p>
<ul>
<li>Wars allocate a share of current national soldiers to each front.</li>
<li>Multi-front wars split/withdraw deployed soldiers as needed.</li>
<li>Direct vassals provide support soldiers to overlord fronts.</li>
</ul>
<p>Peace pressure:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>war_peace_pressure_between(civ_id, other_id)</code> exposes simulation peace</li>
</ul>
<p>  pressure for UI. It uses the active war side and the same peace-desire helper</p>
<p>  used by war resolution.</p>
<ul>
<li>Diplomacy war cards show both sides' peace pressure against the 70 threshold</li>
</ul>
<p>  and communicate that peace can resolve when both sides reach 70.</p>
<p>Battle update:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>war_update_year()</code> calls <code>run_war_year()</code> once per active war per year.</li>
<li>Current design is a 3-year battle model.</li>
<li>Defender can receive technology defense army percent.</li>
<li>Stage 9+ battle chance bonus affects battle chance.</li>
<li>Casualties are applied to population through <code>population_apply_casualties()</code>.</li>
<li>War deaths add disorder and can notify plague system.</li>
</ul>
<p>Peace/outcome:</p>
<ul>
<li>Peace desire increases with disorder, casualties, total active casualties,</li>
</ul>
<p>  and multiple fronts.</p>
<ul>
<li>If both sides have peace desire at least 70, war resolves.</li>
<li>Winner can take bordering provinces; severe outcomes can create vassal state.</li>
<li>Stalemate starts truce.</li>
<li>Severed front ends war with truce.</li>
</ul>
<p>Known issue:</p>
<ul>
<li>Multi-line/multi-front wars are implemented, but exact UX explanation should</li>
</ul>
<p>  call out that soldiers/support are approximated per front rather than stored</p>
<p>  as persistent province armies.</p>
<h2>15. Population</h2>
<p>Source:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>src/sim/population.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/sim/population.h</code></li>
<li><code>src/render/panel_population.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/render/panel_population_page.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/render/panel_country_population.c</code></li>
</ul>
<p>Age bands:</p>
<ul>
<li>0-4</li>
<li>5-17</li>
<li>18-24</li>
<li>25-39</li>
<li>40-54</li>
<li>55-64</li>
<li>65-74</li>
<li>75+</li>
</ul>
<p>Sex:</p>
<ul>
<li>Each cohort has male and female counts.</li>
</ul>
<p>Derived summary:</p>
<ul>
<li>total</li>
<li>male/female</li>
<li>children</li>
<li>working</li>
<li>fertile</li>
<li>recruitable</li>
<li>elder</li>
<li>carrying capacity</li>
<li>pressure</li>
</ul>
<p>Monthly update:</p>
<ul>
<li>Cohorts age by width-based movement.</li>
<li>Births depend on fertile couples, carrying pressure, city stats, owner</li>
</ul>
<p>  disorder, and disorder population-growth percent.</p>
<ul>
<li>Deaths include pressure deaths, child stress from low food/water, and elder</li>
</ul>
<p>  deaths.</p>
<p>Casualties:</p>
<ul>
<li>War casualties remove population from recruitable/working male-heavy cohorts.</li>
<li>Plague deaths remove population across bands by vulnerability.</li>
</ul>
<p>Migration:</p>
<ul>
<li>Ports and maritime systems can migrate people between cities.</li>
<li>Migration can notify plague spread.</li>
</ul>
<h2>16. Resource System</h2>
<p>Source:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>src/world/terrain_query.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/sim/simulation.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/sim/vassal.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/sim/technology.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/sim/disorder.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/render/panel_country_resources.c</code></li>
</ul>
<p>Country summary:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>summarize_country()</code> aggregates owned tile stats and cities.</li>
<li>Technology resource percent modifies resource output.</li>
<li>Disorder productivity percent reduces effective output.</li>
<li>Vassal tribute is then deducted from vassals and added to overlords.</li>
</ul>
<p>Resource score:</p>
<ul>
<li>Used by technology, expansion, disorder, and decision UI.</li>
<li>Built from food, livestock, water, wood, stone, minerals, money, capacity, and</li>
</ul>
<p>  habitability style components depending on context.</p>
<p>Affected systems:</p>
<ul>
<li>Expansion need/threshold.</li>
<li>Technology required years.</li>
<li>Disorder resource pressure.</li>
<li>Population carrying pressure.</li>
<li>Diplomacy resource conflict.</li>
<li>Vassal tribute.</li>
</ul>
<h2>17. Disorder</h2>
<p>Source:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>src/sim/disorder.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/sim/disorder.h</code></li>
<li><code>src/render/panel_country_disorder.c</code></li>
</ul>
<p>Total disorder:</p>
<ul>
<li>Range: 0-100.</li>
<li>Used as debuff for productivity, population growth, and technology.</li>
<li>At 100, immediate collapse attempt path is used.</li>
</ul>
<p>Buckets:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>disorder_resource</code>: population/resource pressure.</li>
<li><code>disorder_plague</code>: plague pressure and plague deaths.</li>
<li><code>disorder_stability</code>: war and civil unrest.</li>
<li><code>disorder_migration</code>: migration/expansion pressure.</li>
<li>Vassal governance burden: separate floor/source shown in UI.</li>
</ul>
<p>Monthly pressure:</p>
<ul>
<li>Resource pressure uses population pressure and scarcity.</li>
<li>Pressure contribution uses scaled bucket values.</li>
</ul>
<p>Recovery:</p>
<ul>
<li>Base recovery.</li>
<li>Governance recovery.</li>
<li>Peace recovery when not at war.</li>
<li>Cohesion recovery during war.</li>
<li>Condition recovery when not at war, pressure is low, and resource score is</li>
</ul>
<p>  healthy.</p>
<ul>
<li>Plague, war, and migration bucket decay have separate rates.</li>
</ul>
<p>Effects:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>disorder_productivity_percent()</code></li>
<li><code>disorder_population_growth_percent()</code></li>
<li><code>disorder_technology_percent()</code></li>
</ul>
<p>UI:</p>
<ul>
<li>Shows pressure cards, recovery stacked bar, active effects, plague status,</li>
</ul>
<p>  and collapse risk.</p>
<h2>18. Plague</h2>
<p>Source:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>src/sim/plague.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/sim/plague.h</code></li>
<li><code>src/sim/sea_lanes.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/render/plague_render.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/render/plague_visual.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/render/panel_plague_page.c</code></li>
</ul>
<p>Random outbreak:</p>
<ul>
<li>Monthly random outbreak attempt has a 4% gate.</li>
<li>Best city is selected by outbreak risk plus random noise.</li>
<li>A city must pass risk threshold and be valid.</li>
</ul>
<p>Random immunity:</p>
<ul>
<li>After a civilization has plague activity end, it receives 50 years</li>
</ul>
<p>  (<code>50 * 12</code> months) of random-outbreak immunity.</p>
<p>City outbreak state:</p>
<ul>
<li>active</li>
<li>infected</li>
<li>severity</li>
<li>months_left</li>
<li>immunity</li>
<li>deaths_total</li>
<li>origin_city</li>
<li>age_months</li>
</ul>
<p>Spread:</p>
<ul>
<li>Local city-to-city spread uses distance, severity, and port-to-port bonus.</li>
<li>Maritime spread uses <code>sea_lanes_plague_contacts_from_city()</code>.</li>
<li>Deep sea lanes use <code>technology_deep_sea_plague_percent()</code> for exposure.</li>
<li>Migration and war casualties can notify plague system.</li>
</ul>
<p>Deaths:</p>
<ul>
<li>Active city plague calls <code>population_apply_city_plague()</code>.</li>
<li>Deaths add plague disorder pressure and plague death pressure.</li>
</ul>
<p>Visuals:</p>
<ul>
<li>Render-only plague animation uses soft dark-green infection clouds, pulsing</li>
</ul>
<p>  city cores, and route exposure intensity.</p>
<ul>
<li>Ver0.2.5 fog cache rebuilds are throttled by <code>FOG_REBUILD_INTERVAL_MS</code> and</li>
</ul>
<p>  expose <code>plague_visual_fog_rebuild_count()</code>,</p>
<p>  <code>plague_visual_last_fog_rebuild_ms()</code>, and</p>
<p>  <code>plague_visual_fog_rebuild_interval_ms()</code> for debug/performance display.</p>
<ul>
<li>Rendering does not mutate simulation state.</li>
</ul>
<h2>19. Collapse and Territory Integrity</h2>
<p>Source:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>src/sim/collapse.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/sim/territory_integrity.c</code></li>
</ul>
<p>Collapse probability:</p>
<ul>
<li>Disorder below 75: no ordinary 25-year collapse risk.</li>
<li>75+: 10%.</li>
<li>80+: 20%.</li>
<li>85+: 30%.</li>
<li>90+: 45%.</li>
<li>95+: 65%.</li>
<li>100: immediate path; ordinary 25-year roll is skipped.</li>
</ul>
<p>Checks:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>collapse_update_decade()</code> is called every 25 years.</li>
<li><code>collapse_update_immediate()</code> checks disorder 100 every month.</li>
</ul>
<p>Block reasons:</p>
<ul>
<li>Not alive.</li>
<li>Max civ slots.</li>
<li>No valid capital region.</li>
<li>No splittable non-capital region.</li>
<li>Only core left.</li>
<li>City cap.</li>
<li>Unknown.</li>
</ul>
<p>Collapse behavior:</p>
<ul>
<li>Capital/core remnant stays with old civ.</li>
<li>Non-capital natural regions can form successor civs.</li>
<li>Successors inherit partial disorder bucket state.</li>
<li>Direct vassals are released on overlord collapse.</li>
<li>Former vassal collapse successors remain independent.</li>
<li>Post-collapse grace clamps disorder buckets and pauses ordinary collapse rolls.</li>
</ul>
<p>Territory integrity:</p>
<ul>
<li>Tracks capital-connected regions.</li>
<li>Disconnected components accumulate disconnected months.</li>
<li>Enclave limit is 300 months.</li>
<li>Disconnected regions can join a better candidate civ or become independent.</li>
<li>Events: enclave joined, independent, failed.</li>
</ul>
<h2>20. Event Log and Debug</h2>
<p>Source:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>src/core/event_log.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/core/game_types.h</code></li>
<li><code>src/core/render_snapshot.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/render/panel_debug.c</code></li>
</ul>
<p>Event types:</p>
<ul>
<li>Generic</li>
<li>Expansion claimed</li>
<li>War started</li>
<li>War front severed</li>
<li>Battle resolved</li>
<li>Truce signed</li>
<li>Collapse succeeded/failed</li>
<li>Plague started/spread/ended</li>
<li>Vassal created/released/transferred/independence/annexed</li>
<li>Performance throttled/slow call/scheduler yield</li>
<li>World generation notice</li>
<li>Disorder changed</li>
<li>Debug notice</li>
<li>Deep sea route created/failed</li>
<li>Civil unrest triggered</li>
<li>Enclave joined/independent/failed</li>
<li>Civ created</li>
<li>Diplomacy peace/tense transition</li>
</ul>
<p>Structured event data:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>EventLogEntry</code> stores type, severity, civ ids, target ids, region/city ids,</li>
</ul>
<p>  params, civ uids, civ snapshots, and raw message.</p>
<ul>
<li>Structured events support bilingual formatting.</li>
<li>Legacy raw events are parsed into event types when pushed by raw text.</li>
</ul>
<p>Ver0.2.4 fixes:</p>
<ul>
<li>Snapshot event formatting uses the copied event entry, keeping displayed text</li>
</ul>
<p>  and clickable country payload paired.</p>
<ul>
<li>Historical event country chips validate <code>civ_uid</code> before highlighting so a</li>
</ul>
<p>  reused civ slot is not highlighted incorrectly.</p>
<p>Ver0.2.5 additions:</p>
<ul>
<li>Peace and tense relation transitions use structured event types and can drive</li>
</ul>
<p>  diplomacy map animation.</p>
<ul>
<li><code>VASSAL_RELEASE_FAILED_NO_OVERLORD</code> currently uses a debug/raw fallback path.</li>
</ul>
<p>Debug panel:</p>
<ul>
<li>Event filters: all, expansion/routes, war/diplomacy, collapse/plague,</li>
</ul>
<p>  performance/system.</p>
<ul>
<li>Scroll can freeze; Top unfreezes and returns to latest.</li>
<li>Country chips can highlight countries on map.</li>
<li>Performance sections show snapshot age, scheduler queue, render cache rebuilds,</li>
</ul>
<p>  slow calls, and route diagnostics.</p>
<h2>21. Performance Architecture</h2>
<p>Source:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>src/sim/simulation_scheduler.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/sim/simulation_worker.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/sim/simulation_month.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/core/dirty_flags.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/core/profiler.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/core/render_snapshot.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/render/render.c</code></li>
</ul>
<p>Scheduler:</p>
<ul>
<li>Auto-run queues bounded month work.</li>
<li>Pending month backlog is capped/trimmed.</li>
<li>Speed targets are now slower and more observational by default: 10000, 5000,</li>
</ul>
<p>  1000, 250, and 100 ms/month.</p>
<ul>
<li>Faster speed targets receive larger bounded work budgets.</li>
<li>Heavy phases are split into batches.</li>
</ul>
<p>Worker:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>simulation_worker_start()</code> starts background simulation worker path.</li>
<li>The frame path consumes completed visual ticks.</li>
<li>Diplomacy map animation activity can request repaint even when simulation did</li>
</ul>
<p>  not complete a month.</p>
<p>Dirty flags:</p>
<ul>
<li>World.</li>
<li>Territory/ownership.</li>
<li>Province.</li>
<li>Population.</li>
<li>Plague.</li>
<li>Maritime.</li>
<li>Labels.</li>
<li>UI/render revisions.</li>
</ul>
<p>Render cache:</p>
<ul>
<li>Terrain, coast, political, border/static, and UI caches are independent.</li>
<li>Dynamic overlays avoid rebuilding static layers.</li>
<li>Label redraw does not force full map rebuild.</li>
<li>Stale UI cache fallback keeps UI visible if snapshot data is not fresh.</li>
</ul>
<p>Profiler:</p>
<ul>
<li>Tracks month phases, render rebuilds, GDI recreates, scanned regions/tiles,</li>
</ul>
<p>  expansion scans/claims, maritime path search, sea lane stats, contour rebuilds,</p>
<p>  terrain presentation mode, scheduler step, and slow calls.</p>
<ul>
<li>Ver0.2.5 debug/performance panel additionally exposes plague fog rebuild count,</li>
</ul>
<p>  last rebuild time, rebuild interval, active route-port nodes, shallow candidate</p>
<p>  edges, accepted shallow lanes, deep lanes, missing-admin skips, and lane-cap</p>
<p>  skips.</p>
<p>Known hot paths:</p>
<ul>
<li>Full-map resource scans.</li>
<li>Region/territory scans.</li>
<li>Contour/path rebuilds.</li>
<li>Route-potential rebuild and sea lane selection.</li>
<li>Plague fog rebuilds when many infected city visuals are active.</li>
<li>Blocking validation probes.</li>
</ul>
<h2>22. Save / Load</h2>
<p>Source:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>src/io/map_save.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/io/map_save_regions.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/io/map_save_legacy.h</code></li>
<li><code>src/game/game.c</code></li>
<li><code>src/ui/pause_menu.c</code></li>
</ul>
<p>Implemented:</p>
<ul>
<li>Pause menu has Resume, Version Log, Save Map, Load Map, Exit.</li>
<li>Save Map opens Save As dialog.</li>
<li>Load Map opens file dialog.</li>
<li>Save/load routes through <code>game_request_after_load_map()</code> after loading.</li>
<li>Natural regions have dedicated save/read helpers.</li>
<li>Ver0.2.6.b save version is <code>MAP_SAVE_VERSION 7</code>.</li>
</ul>
<p>Natural region compatibility:</p>
<ul>
<li>Version 7 saves/loads the current <code>NaturalRegion</code> structure, including</li>
</ul>
<p>  <code>name_id</code>.</p>
<ul>
<li>Version 5-6 region blocks are read through a legacy region struct that lacks</li>
</ul>
<p>  <code>name_id</code>; loaded regions get <code>name_id = -1</code> and then</p>
<p>  <code>province_names_assign_missing()</code>.</p>
<ul>
<li>Version 4 and older legacy region reads also initialize disconnection fields and</li>
</ul>
<p>  missing province names.</p>
<p>To confirm:</p>
<ul>
<li>Save format details should be documented only after reading <code>map_save.c</code> in a</li>
</ul>
<p>  dedicated save-format pass.</p>
<h2>23. Known Issues and Technical Debt</h2>
<p>Version metadata:</p>
<ul>
<li>Freeze target is Ver0.2.6.b, and <code>src/core/version.h</code> reports</li>
</ul>
<p>  <code>WORLD_SIM_VERSION "0.2.6.b"</code>. The code version marker matches this release.</p>
<p>  macro should be updated in a code-authorized task. Gameplay-changing: no.</p>
<p>Architecture:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>core/game_types.h</code> still exposes broad global state and compatibility includes.</li>
</ul>
<p>  Direction: continue using narrower headers for new modules.</p>
<p>  Gameplay-changing: no.</p>
<p>Rendering:</p>
<ul>
<li>Snapshot migration is partial; some render panels read globals directly.</li>
</ul>
<p>  Direction: migrate read-heavy panel data into snapshot or stable copied views.</p>
<p>  Gameplay-changing: no.</p>
<p>Maritime rendering:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>src/render/maritime_render.c</code> is present but comments say active build uses</li>
</ul>
<p>  <code>route_render.c</code>.</p>
<p>  Direction: remove or clearly mark inactive after confirming build history.</p>
<p>  Gameplay-changing: no.</p>
<p>Route potential migration:</p>
<ul>
<li>Ver0.2.5 introduces <code>route_potential</code> while older maritime route structures</li>
</ul>
<p>  still exist for compatibility/render snapshot paths. Direction: future docs</p>
<p>  should keep route-potential graph, active sea lanes, and legacy</p>
<p>  <code>MaritimeRoute</code> separate. Gameplay-changing: no for docs; yes if route</p>
<p>  selection behavior is changed.</p>
<p>Diplomacy / vassal docs:</p>
<ul>
<li>Older version logs mention a vassal governance formula different from current</li>
</ul>
<p>  README wording. Current official docs should be regenerated from code when the</p>
<p>  exact expression changes.</p>
<p>  Gameplay-changing: no if docs-only; yes if formula changes.</p>
<p>War UI:</p>
<ul>
<li>Per-province armies are estimates; persistent province armies are not stored.</li>
</ul>
<p>  Direction: document as estimate, not simulation fact.</p>
<p>  Gameplay-changing: yes if changed into real province armies.</p>
<p>Events:</p>
<ul>
<li>Legacy raw events still coexist with structured events.</li>
</ul>
<p>  Direction: keep raw compatibility but prefer structured pushes.</p>
<p>  Gameplay-changing: no.</p>
<p>Localization:</p>
<ul>
<li>Tables include bilingual text. Tool output can show mojibake depending on</li>
</ul>
<p>  terminal/codepage even though build flags use UTF-8.</p>
<p>  Direction: preserve UTF-8 and verify in app rendering.</p>
<p>  Gameplay-changing: no.</p>
<p>Performance:</p>
<ul>
<li>Blocking probes are not representative of UI scheduler behavior.</li>
</ul>
<p>  Direction: keep probe results separate from runtime UX claims.</p>
<p>  Gameplay-changing: no.</p>
<h2>24. Version Notes for Ver0.2.6.b</h2>
<p>Ver0.2.6.b is a code-settled documentation freeze based on the current working</p>
<p>tree and the previous Ver0.2.5 official documentation.</p>
<p>Implemented according to source diff:</p>
<ul>
<li>World generation orchestration was split into <code>game_worldgen</code> with progress</li>
</ul>
<p>  stages, repaint callbacks, and route stats capture.</p>
<ul>
<li>Worldgen progress overlay, World-tab progress card, and debug worldgen timing</li>
</ul>
<p>  rows were added.</p>
<ul>
<li>Province naming, province labels, snapshot region names, and save version 7</li>
</ul>
<p>  region-name persistence were added.</p>
<ul>
<li>Country overview recent-events cards were added with per-country event filtering</li>
</ul>
<p>  and clickable identity-checked country chips.</p>
<ul>
<li>Diplomacy contact kinds were added for land, shallow sea, deep sea, and vassal</li>
</ul>
<p>  proxy contact. Distant stale relations can decay back to none.</p>
<ul>
<li>War-front detection now uses diplomacy contact kinds, and war cards show</li>
</ul>
<p>  simulation-backed peace pressure.</p>
<ul>
<li>Route-potential and sea-lane caps/stats were expanded, including deep-backbone</li>
</ul>
<p>  connectivity diagnostics.</p>
<ul>
<li>Visible map mode buttons are now Political, Geography, Climate, Regions, and</li>
</ul>
<p>  Routes.</p>
<p>To confirm:</p>
<ul>
<li>The source version macro says <code>0.2.6.b</code>. This document follows the user</li>
</ul>
<p>  freeze label Ver0.2.6.b and records the updated code marker.</p>
